question.resolution_criteria:
This question will be resolve as "Yes" if 95% or more of Nigerians aged 18 or older have an account at a bank or financial institution before January 1, 2025.  This question will resolve according to data from the [Central Bank of Nigeria](https://www.cbn.gov.ng/out/2019/ccd/q2%202019%20financial%20inclusion%20newsletter_final_08.08.19.pdf); if no such data is available, or said data is known to be inaccurate, data from [The World Bank](https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/fx.own.totl.zs?locations=NG) may be considered, or from credible independent researchers.

If the data shows less than 95% of the population with a bank account through 2024, or If no such data is available by March 1, 2026, this question will resolve negatively
question.background_info:
An important concept in economic development is [Financial Inclusion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_inclusion): the degree which a population has access to affordable, convenient, and reliable banking and financial services.   One basic measure of financial inclusion is the percent of a population with a bank account.  According to the [World Bank](https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/account-at-financial-institution?tab=chart&country=~NGA), 39.7% of Nigerians had a bank account in 2017, an increase from 29.7% in 2011. 


[Motta, V. 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11187-018-0082-9) found a positive relationship between access to external finance and labor productivity of small/medium businesses.

In July 2019 Godwin Emefiele, Governor of the Central Bank of Nigeria, [set a goal](https://www.cbn.gov.ng/out/2019/ccd/q2%202019%20financial%20inclusion%20newsletter_final_08.08.19.pdf) to reach 95% of the population with a bank account by 2024.

This question resolves positively if, following the next Australian federal election, the governor-general of Australia swears in a prime minister supplied by the Liberal/National Coalition or by the Liberal Party.

It resolves negatively if the governor-general swears in a prime minister supplied by another party or coalition

If no party is able to form a stable government following the next election, the question will resolve according to the results of the first election where a party is able to form a stable government.

If the political structure of Australia is changed such that the head of government is no longer nominated by parties in a democratically elected house of the legislature, this question will resolve ambiguously.

This question will close when voting closes for the eastern states (NSW, Victoria, Queensland) on election day

### Research Summary
The research indicates that as the 2025 Australian federal election approaches, the political landscape is characterized by a significant decline in support for both the Labor Party and the Coalition, with Labor currently holding 68.5% and the Coalition at 31.5% in a two-party preferred vote. This marks an all-time low for both parties, with nearly a third of voters leaning towards independents and other parties. Polling data suggests that the Coalition is gaining ground, with some surveys indicating that they may secure a majority of seats in the House of Representatives, potentially positioning Peter Dutton as the next prime minister. However, there is considerable uncertainty, as the election is expected to be closely contested, particularly in key marginal seats across various states.

The Coalition's campaign strategies include proposals to end work-from-home arrangements for government employees and the revival of the controversial Safer Communities Fund, which has faced criticism for favoring Coalition electorates. Despite the Coalition's rising support in polls, Labor remains confident in its ability to address voter concerns, particularly regarding the cost of living. The election is anticipated to be influenced by factors such as the emergence of independents and the Greens, as well as the urban-rural divide, making the outcome difficult to predict. Overall, the election is shaping up to be a tight race, with a hung parliament being a likely scenario.

## Report 1 Research

As the 2025 Australian federal election approaches, political polls are being released regularly. **The tally room, like the sure thing that was Bob Hawke, is no more**
The national tally room, a historic venue for Australian election results, has been closed. The room, where Bob Hawke's famous election win was announced, was a theatrical event where reporters and spectators would gather to witness the results. Hawke's victory, which saw him trounce Malcolm Fraser's Coalition, was marked by a chaotic scene, with reporters' typewriters and a television cameraman causing a commotion. As the country prepares for another federal election, it seems unlikely that we will witness a similar moment of unambiguous triumph, with election nights at the tally room now a thing of the past. As Anthony Albanese prepares to announce the election, it's worth reflecting on the history of the tally room and the excitement it once generated, with Fraser breaking down in tears shortly before Hawke's victory was announced, saying, 'It was a great day.'

**Coalition plots to end to WFH for thousands of Aussie workers**
The Coalition has announced plans to end the unlimited work-from-home (WFH) rights for tens of thousands of government staff if they win the federal election. Opposition finance spokesperson Jane Hume said a Liberal government would make all government employees work in the office five days a week, citing the need for a 'culture that focuses on the dignity of serving the public.' However, she clarified that exceptions would be made when they 'work for everyone, rather than enforced on teams by the individual.' question.resolution_criteria:
This question resolves positively if, following the next Australian federal election, the governor-general of Australia swears in a prime minister supplied by the Liberal/National Coalition or by the Liberal Party.

It resolves negatively if the governor-general swears in a prime minister supplied by another party or coalition

If no party is able to form a stable government following the next election, the question will resolve according to the results of the first election where a party is able to form a stable government.

If the political structure of Australia is changed such that the head of government is no longer nominated by parties in a democratically elected house of the legislature, this question will resolve ambiguously.

This question will close when voting closes for the eastern states (NSW, Victoria, Queensland) on election day
